05475nam a22008895i 9780231534222DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013963206  a(OCoLC)1029812400  a(OCoLC)1032686343  a(OCoLC)1037971468  a(OCoLC)1041971197  a(OCoLC)1046613214  a(OCoLC)1046997230  a(OCoLC)1049626104  a(OCoLC)1054881916  a97802315342227 a10.7312/clay135762doi  a(DE-B1597)458755  a(OCoLC)979742456  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a201/.6522300aPracticing Science, Living Faith :bInterviews with Twelve Leading Scientists /ced. by Philip Clayton, Jim Schaal. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b12 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Series in Science and Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. ]ane Goodall -- t2. Hendrik Pieter Barendregt -- t3. Khalil Chamcham -- t4. Donna Auguste -- t5. Ursula Goodenough -- t6. Thomas Odhiambo -- t7. Faraneh Vargha-Khadem -- t8. Pauline Rudd -- t9. Satoto -- t10. Paula Tallal -- t11. Henry Thompson -- t12. Robert Pollack -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwelve scientists from diverse backgrounds and disciplines demonstrate that it is indeed possible for profound intellectuals to integrate the life of science with the life of faith. In honest and inspiring interviews, they describe the difficult though rewarding process of reconciling their faith with their science and reveal the ways in which the two spheres can not only coexist but also mutually enhance each other.Jane Goodall begins the conversation by emphasizing the importance of recognizing the "spark of spirit" that runs through all creatures, human and animal. Robert Pollack discusses his motivations for opening a major center for the study of science and religion at Columbia University. Khalil Chamcham, a Moroccan astrophysicist and devout Muslim, moves from the study of galaxy formation to a new dialogue between Islam and the West. Thomas Odhiambo, a Kenyan entomologist, helps to bring sustainable agriculture to sub-Saharan Africa by uniting African animist and Christian traditions, and Henry Thompson, a computer scientist, utilizes his Quaker practice in both his science and his work as a mediator. Thoughtful and compelling, these and other scientists recount a rich integration of science and religion in their practice, their experience, and their approach to their work. Some find a deep harmony between the life of faith and the practice of science, whereas others struggle with the ongoing tensions. These original interviews range across the metaphysical, ethical, and religious implications of cutting-edge research. Taken together, they offer a unique picture of how scientists make peace with their work and their spirituality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aReligion and science. 0aScientifiquesvEntretiens. 0aScientifiquesvVie religieuse. 0aScientistsvInterviews. 0aScientistsvReligious life. 0aScientistsxReligious life. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aClayton, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClayton, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPhillips, William D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, William.1 aRichardson, W. Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaal, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaal, Jim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTit